The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) is granting Liberty Center Schools a waiver to feed all students breakfast and lunch for free through the Seamless Summer Program. This program will begin on September 10, 2020 and operate until December 31, 2020, or until the funds are depleted, whichever comes first. As the Seamless Summer Program will not last the entire school year, we are asking families who have qualified or could qualify for free or reduced meals to please complete the free and reduced form, which can be found on the district website. If you have any questions please contact Donna Eickholt, Lunchroom Supervisor, at deickholt@libertycenterschools.org or 419-533-0006.

Sincerely,

Richard A. Peters
Superintendent

post_text:
Dear Liberty Center Parents, Students, Staff, and Community:

Governor DeWine provided guidance to school districts in early July on how school will open in the fall. With this guidance, we have collaborated with area Superintendents and the Henry County Health Commissioner to develop a county re-start plan. The Henry County Schools Common Re-Start Agreement is included with this letter.

In the coming days and weeks, we will be working to finalize our district plan that will align with the county document. We are striving to ensure the safest environment possible for all students and staff. While our goal is to have children in the building full time for instruction, we will adhere to all of the required procedures and guidelines as student and staff safety is our top priority. Please watch for additional communication from the district regarding the 2020-21 school year.

Sincerely,

Richard A. Peters
text:
Dear Liberty Center Parents, Students, Staff, and Community:

Governor DeWine provided guidance to school districts in early July on how school will open in the fall. With this guidance, we have collaborated with area Superintendents and the Henry County Health Commissioner to develop a county re-start plan. The Henry County Schools Common Re-Start Agreement is included with this letter.

In the coming days and weeks, we will be working to finalize our district plan that will align with the county document. We are striving to ensure the safest environment possible for all students and staff. While our goal is to have children in the building full time for instruction, we will adhere to all of the required procedures and guidelines as student and staff safety is our top priority. Please watch for additional communication from the district regarding the 2020-21 school year.

Sincerely,

Richard A. Peters

The goal is to have the project completed by the first home varsity football game of the 2020 season.

Good Afternoon,

The water line in the K-12 school building has been repaired and water service has been restored. However, the water will need additional testing before consumption. This testing will take place on Monday. School will be in session on Monday, but the drinking fountains will not be available until the testing is complete. Students may bring bottled water to school and additional bottled water will be available. Breakfast and lunch will be provided by our cafeteria staff with the necessary precautions taking place.

Thank you for your understanding,

Richie Peters, Superintendent
Liberty Center Local Schools

Picture re-takes originally scheduled for this coming Wednesday, November 6th, have been postponed. We have been in contact with Lifetouch. Unfortunately, there has been a delay in the processing of the elementary pictures. As soon as those pictures arrive, we will schedule our re-take day for elementary, middle and high school students. Lifetouch apologizes for the inconvenience this has caused and would like to thank you for your patience. Please contact your child's respective office with any questions.

LC XC "Men in Black" Punch Ticket To State Championships! The Liberty Center Boys Cross Country Team finished 7th out of 23 teams to claim the final state qualifying spot out of the Tiffin Regional. There were 188 runners competing in this Regional competition. This is the seventh consecutive year that the team has achieved this honor. The race featured eight state ranked teams (#3 New London, #5 Columbus Grove, #10 Holgate, #11 Hopewell-Loudon, #12 Sandusky St. Mary's, #16 Ashland Crestview, #17 Minster, and #18 Liberty Center), with only seven qualifying spots available. Good afternoon,

During today’s afternoon dismissal, a motorized vehicle driven by a minor without a driver’s license drove through the student pickup line. Fortunately, no students or staff were injured. The vehicle was stopped immediately, and the minor was removed from the vehicle. The situation has been turned over to our school resource officer and the Henry County Sheriff’s Department. We greatly appreciate the admirable response of our staff and the cooperation of the parents picking up their children. The safety of our students and staff is always our top
priority

Richard A. Peters, Superintendent
Liberty Center Local Schools

"LC XC Lady Tigers Keep Invitational Streak Alive!" The Liberty Center Lady Tigers Cross Country Team won a "Team Championship" for the sixth time this season at this year's Springfield 'Saturday Night Lights' Invitational. This is the team's fourth consecutive team title. Liberty Center won the title with a combined score of 19 points, followed by Gibsonburg (63 Points), and Springfield (75 Points). Leading the way for the Lady Tigers was Hope Oelkrug (Individual Champion), Sydney Miller (2nd Place), Dalayna Ashbaugh (3rd Place), Mallory Stark (5th Place), Cassie Elieff (9th Place), Bailey Johnson (11th Place), and Gwyn Murrey (13th Place). The Tigers also swept the first five places in the… More

Liberty Center Cross Country
September 23, 2019 at 12:12 AM ·

"LC XC Men In Black Battle for 4th Place at Widewater Invitational!" The Liberty Center Boys Cross Country team finished 4th out of 15 teams at this year's Widewater Invitational. The race featured 4 teams that are currently ranked in the Top 20 of the State Coaches Poll (including state ranked Columbus Grove-#5; Holgate-#9; Hopewell-Loudon-#12; and Liberty Center #14). There were 165 athletes competing in this year's competition. The Tigers tallied 127 points in the race. Columbus Grove claimed the team title with a score of 65 points, followed by Holgate (77 Points), Hopewell-Loudon (79 Points), LC (127 Points), and Woodmore (167 Points). Leading the way for the Tigers was Nathaniel Elieff (12th), Chris Miles (27th), Kenny Miles (29th), Drew Bowser (32nd), Derek Dulle (43rd), Matthew Marlow (44th), and Ethan Borstelman (85th). Congratulations to all of the runners competing on Saturday in what turned out to be a rather sunny and warm day for racing! The next stop for the Tiger Harriers will be at the Old Fort Invitational on Saturday, September 28th, 2019.

Liberty Center Cross Country
September 9, 2019 at 1:19 AM ·

Congratulations to Senior LC XC Tiger Harrier Chris Miles on his incredible display of sportsmanship at this year's Tiffin XC Carnival! Despite competing in his final Carnival race and being on season record pace, Chris stopped sprinting in his final 100m of the race to assist a fellow cross country runner who had collapsed near the Finish Line. Chris assisted this athlete to the finish where he was treated medically. There is no substitute for doing the right thing! The LC XC Coaching Staff commends your actions on Saturday Chris, and we are so proud of you!

August 26, 2019 at 12:37 AM ·

LC XC Lady Tigers Claim Their First Championship Of The Season! The Lady Tigers Cross Country Team won their first team title of the 2019 season by winning the prestigious Seneca East Tiger Classic Cross Country Invitational. The Lady Harriers scored 48 points to win the team title, followed by Mount Gilead (116 Points), and Smithville (128 Points). The race featured over 220 runners and 19 teams. Leading the way for the Lady Tigers was Hope Oelkrug (4th), Sydney Miller (8th), Dalayna Ashbaugh (13th), Cassie Elieff (14th), Mallory Stark (16th), Sophie Long (24th), Bailey Johnson (37th), Gwyn Murray (40th), Regan Dulle (52nd), Alexus Shaneyfelt (69th), Ashley Rall (81st), Keirstin McClure (116th), and Erica Minnich (190th). The Lady Tigers next appearance will be at the Greenville "Treaty City" Invitational in Greenville, Ohio on August 31st.

post_text: Open House is Monday, August 19 from 4:30-6. While you are here,stop by and enjoy the Food Trucks
shared_text:
Sara Donald Lawniczak
July 29, 2019 at 11:24 AM ·

Liberty Center Elementary Open House is Monday, August 19 from 4:30-6. We are trying something new this year and are having food trucks come. Kona Ice Findlay (cash or credit/debit), The Snack Shack (CASH ONLY), Koral Hamburg Food Truck (cash or credit/debit) and 2nd Chance Food Truck (cash or credit/debit) will be serving from 4-7. They will be set up in the parking spots along the fence by the football field. There will a few tables and chairs outside to eat at. Feel free to have a seat or take it to go after you meet your amazing teachers. Please keep the food/drinks outside so the trash is contained to one area for an easier clean up. Check out the menus in the pics. Don't forget to bring back your Kona Ice cups because they get cheaper refills for the life of the cup. A portion of Kona Ice sales will come back to PTO. The community is welcome to enjoy the trucks too. With this being a new idea maybe throw a blanket in your car or a few chairs if you plan on eating there. I didn't want to have a ton of tables and chairs set up and they not be used.

post_text:
Good afternoon,

This message is to provide clear, accurate information to the Liberty Center community regarding last Thursday evening’s incident. School officials and the Henry County Sheriff’s department began the investigation process Thursday night immediately after receiving information of a possible threat to the school. The student in question was not permitted to attend school until the investigation was completed. The results of the investigation determined that there was no threat made toward the school. Additionally, there was never a threatening note as was indicated by a social media post. The student in question will not be attending school for the remainder of the school year. This decision is for this student’s well-being. There are no criminal charges or school consequences pending against this student.

Richard A. Peters, Superintendent

Liberty Center Local Schools

post_text:
Good Afternoon,

School officials, in conjunction with the Henry County Sheriff’s Department, thoroughly investigated the potential threat that was brought to our attention last evening. While there is no evidence that a viable threat to harm students or staff was made, we appreciate the collaborative effort by local law enforcement to ensure everyone’s safety. We will continue to monitor this situation closely. As always, the safety of our students and staff is our primary mission at Liberty Center Schools.

Richard A. Peters, Superintendent
Liberty Center Schools

Good afternoon,

During today’s afternoon dismissal, a motorized vehicle attempting to leave the parking lot struck a pole barrier. Fortunately, the students and staff near the incident were not injured. We greatly appreciate the admirable response of the elementary staff and the cooperation of the parents picking up their children. The safety of our students and staff is our top priority. In light of this incident, we will continue to review our dismissal procedures to maintain this goal.

Richard A. Peters, Superintendent
Liberty Center Local Schools

Liberty Center Schools Band Program
May 7, 2019 at 10:20 PM ·

ELECTRONICS RECYCLING CHALLENGE RESULTS
The results are in and CONGRATULATIONS are in order! We have once again won the electronics recycling challenge, earning $1,763.67 for the band and choir programs. The results are below:

1st - Liberty Center 16,263 pounds
2nd - Patrick Henry 12,116 pounds
3rd - Napoleon 11,488 pounds
4th - Holgate 6,982 pounds

Between all four schools, we collected and recycled 46,849 pounds of electronics across Henry County!

Thanks to all for your help and donations!

Liberty Center Cheerleading
April 6, 2019 at 1:35 PM ·

🐯MINI CHEER 2019🐯
They are getting geared up for a another successful year of mini cheer! This area of our program is the MOST IMPORTANT to us because it lays the foundation for our entire program! It allows girls to be exposed at an earlier age which will allow them to have more experience under their belts when they get to jr high and high school. (It makes a big difference!) Mini Cheer allows girls to learn more coordination, technique, and possible tumbling skills. If you have any questions, contact Sydney Davis. Also, follow the LC Mini Competition Team on Facebook to see updates and more information. GO TIGERS!

We look forward to a great season.

The pre season is over.

Time to WIN TODAY!
